<typeStatus id="5118FAE49B26370EFAD1169AFCF7FEDD" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">syntypes</typeStatus>
consist of one male and one female. I have selected the male to serve as 
<typeStatus id="5118FAE49B26370EFB93175AFBEDFEBD" box="[1048,1146,318,341]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">lectotype</typeStatus>
and labeled it as such, and provide images of the habitus, male genitalia, and labels of that specimen (
<figureCitation id="169858C39B26370EFC7D171AFBA0FE7D" box="[1014,1079,382,405]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[150,181,2064,2083]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,799,2034]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1437,798,2034]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1. Dorsal habitus of Guatemalan Hydrochus species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879762" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879762/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="169858C39B26370EFBC8171AFBC5FE7D" box="[1091,1106,382,405]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[151,182,2059,2078]" captionTargetBox="[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Hydrochus debilis Sharp, 1882, habitus and male genitalia of lectotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879766" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879766/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="169858C39B26370EFBD6171AFBFBFE7D" box="[1117,1132,382,405]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[150,181,2064,2083]" captionTargetBox="[266,1320,1467,2045]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[266,1320,1467,2045]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 8 Hydrochus lectotype labels.A – H. obscurus Sharp, 1882; B – H. debilis Sharp, 1882." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879778" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879778/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">8</figureCitation>
). The other 
<typeStatus id="5118FAE49B26370EFB62171AFAABFE7D" box="[1257,1340,382,405]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">syntype</typeStatus>
has been labeled 
<typeStatus id="5118FAE49B26370EFC1B17FAFBB4FE5D" box="[912,1059,414,437]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">paralectotype</typeStatus>
. One additional specimen provided by the NHM as ‘Possible typeʼ is a different species, from 
<collectingCountry id="F6B404D69B26370EFCB717BAFC06FE1D" box="[828,913,478,501]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. One of the 
<typeStatus id="5118FAE49B26370EFB9617BAFBEDFE1D" box="[1053,1146,478,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">syntypes</typeStatus>
bears a 
<typeStatus id="5118FAE49B26370EFB5D17BAFAAFFE1D" box="[1238,1336,478,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">lectotype</typeStatus>
label, by 
<collectorName id="235621909B26370EFCB7179AFC45FDFD" box="[828,978,510,533]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">J. L. Hellman</collectorName>
, but this designation was never published. 
<collectorName id="235621909B26370EFCB7147AFCFCFDDD" box="[828,875,542,565]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">This</collectorName>
label has been reversed and “unpub.” written on the reverse side.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C6B917CD9B26370FFCB7143AFE2AFEDD" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="294" pageId="2" pageNumber="293" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B26370FFCB7143AFE2AFEDD" blockId="2.[828,1437,190,757]" lastBlockId="3.[151,760,188,565]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="294" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis id="BCD798549B26370EFCB7143AFBDFFD9D" bold="true" box="[828,1096,606,629]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Guatemalan species, 
<taxonomicName id="49A33FC59B26370EFCB7141BFC32FD7D" box="[828,933,638,662]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilis">
<emphasis id="BCD798549B26370EFCB7141BFC32FD7D" box="[828,933,638,662]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">H. debilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recognized by the combination of moderate size (ca. 
<quantity id="495BE9A39B26370EFC1014FAFBABFD5D" box="[923,1084,670,693]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.885" metricValueMax="3.08" metricValueMin="2.69" pageId="2" pageNumber="293" unit="mm" value="2.885" valueMax="3.08" valueMin="2.69">2.69–3.08 mm</quantity>
), the densely punctate pronotum with deep foveae, and the elytral sculpture, each elytron having four raised interstriae: 3 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B26370EFB0E14B8FB05FD02" attach="left" box="[1157,1170,732,746]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">rd</superScript>
slightly raised over basal ¼, 4 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFF4C16D8FF44FF22" attach="left" box="[199,211,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
raised in area anterior to large callus of 5 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFD1C16D8FD34FF22" attach="none" box="[663,675,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
, 5 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFD3416D8FD5CFF22" attach="left" box="[703,715,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
raised from about anterior ¼ to midlength, and usual callus of 5 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFF4F1698FF47FEE2" attach="none" box="[196,208,252,266]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
. The distinctive male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="169858C39B27370FFDB7169AFD16FEFD" box="[572,641,254,277]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[151,182,2059,2078]" captionTargetBox="[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Hydrochus debilis Sharp, 1882, habitus and male genitalia of lectotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879766" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879766/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
; described below) are also diagnostic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DADC14CE9B26370EFF1C1E6FFCA0F7F6" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879766" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3879766" box="[151,823,2059,2078]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879766/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="293" startId="2.[151,182,2059,2078]" targetBox="[204,1384,841,2039]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B26370EFF1C1E6FFCA0F7F6" blockId="2.[151,823,2059,2078]" box="[151,823,2059,2078]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">
Fig. 2. 
<taxonomicName id="49A33FC59B26370EFF5F1E6FFE4AF7F6" authority="Sharp, 1882" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" box="[212,477,2059,2078]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilis">
<emphasis id="BCD798549B26370EFF5F1E6FFEF8F7F6" box="[212,367,2059,2078]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="293">Hydrochus debilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EA3239B79B26370EFEFF1E6FFE4AF7F6" author="SHARP D." box="[372,477,2059,2078]" pageId="2" pageNumber="293" pagination="1 - 144" refId="ref6023" refString="SHARP D. 1882: Insecta. Coleoptera. Vol. 1, part 2 (Haliplidae, Dytiscidae, Gyrinidae, Hydrophilidae, Heteroceridae, Parnidae, Georissidae, Cyathoceridae, Staphylinidae). Pp 1 - 144. In: GODMAN F. D. &amp; SALVIN O.: Biologia Centrali-Americana. Volume 16. Taylor and Francis, London, xv + 824 pp." type="book chapter" year="1882">Sharp, 1882</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, habitus and male genitalia of lectotype.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C6B917CD9B273708FF1C175AFE95FC1D" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="295" pageId="3" pageNumber="294" type="description">
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B27370FFF1C175AFB04FEDD" blockId="3.[151,760,188,565]" lastBlockId="3.[828,1437,190,565]" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">
<emphasis id="BCD798549B27370FFF1C175AFEA9FEBD" bold="true" box="[151,318,318,341]" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">Redescription.</emphasis>
Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation id="169858C39B27370FFDCF175AFD1DFEBD" box="[580,650,318,341]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[151,182,2059,2078]" captionTargetBox="[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Hydrochus debilis Sharp, 1882, habitus and male genitalia of lectotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879766" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879766/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Size (in mm): 
<typeStatus id="5118FAE49B27370FFF51173AFEDEFE9D" box="[218,329,350,373]" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">Lectotype</typeStatus>
: body (length to elytral apices / width) 2.88 / 1.04; head width 0.69; pronotum length / width 0.75 / 0.71; PA 0.67; PB 0.56; elytra length / width 1.85 / 1.04. Body size moderate (ca. 
<quantity id="495BE9A39B27370FFE1F17DAFDBDFE3D" box="[404,554,446,469]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.885" metricValueMax="3.08" metricValueMin="2.69" pageId="3" pageNumber="294" unit="mm" value="2.885" valueMax="3.08" valueMin="2.69">2.69–3.08 mm</quantity>
in Guatemalan specimens). Dorsum dark grey to black, with very slight if any iridescence, elytra with black spots. Legs dark brown, with tibiofemoral joints slightly darker. Punctation on elytra ca. 2–4× that of pronotum. Elytra interstriae ca. 0.5–1.0× strial puncture diameter. Interstria 9 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFB4816B8FB58FF02" attach="left" box="[1219,1231,220,234]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
more convex than others, overhanging 10 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFBBF1698FBD7FEE2" attach="left" box="[1076,1088,252,266]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
interstria. Callus on 5 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFAB81698FAA8FEE2" attach="left" box="[1331,1343,252,266]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
in usual area, large, very strongly raised.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B27370FFCD1175AFC37FE3D" blockId="3.[828,1437,190,565]" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">Pronotum length ca. equal width, widest at ca. anterior 1/3, narrowed at base, sides sinuate, minutely denticulate; anterior margin slightly bisinuate; depressions deep, reliefs sharply raised, depressions and reliefs densely punctate.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B273708FCD117BAFEEEFEBD" blockId="3.[828,1437,190,565]" lastBlockId="4.[151,760,188,1013]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="295" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">
Elytra with spaces between strial punctures narrow ridges to ca. 0.5× their diameter; 3 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFB061798FB0DFDE2" attach="left" box="[1165,1178,508,522]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">rd</superScript>
interstria slightly raised over basal fourth; 4 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B27370FFB981478FB88FDC2" attach="left" box="[1043,1055,540,554]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">th</superScript>
interstria raised in area anterior to callus of 5 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B203708FE8F16D8FE87FF22" attach="right" box="[260,272,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">th</superScript>
; 5 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B203708FEA116D8FEA1FF22" attach="left" box="[298,310,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">th</superScript>
interstria raised from about anterior fourth to midlength, raised area separated from callus of 5 
<superScript id="79D6E90E9B203708FD4316B8FD43FF02" attach="left" box="[712,724,220,234]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">th</superScript>
by very slight depression; apices rather sharply conjointly rounded in dorsal view, in lateral view outer margin with moderate angulation.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DADC14CE9B27370FFF1C1E6DFC8EF7F4" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879768" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3879768" box="[151,793,2057,2076]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879768/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="294" startId="3.[151,182,2057,2076]" targetBox="[220,1373,626,2023]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B27370FFF1C1E6DFC8EF7F4" blockId="3.[151,793,2057,2076]" box="[151,793,2057,2076]" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">
Fig. 3. 
<taxonomicName id="49A33FC59B27370FFF5F1E6DFEEDF7F4" authority="Perkins, 2020" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2020" box="[212,378,2057,2076]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="directus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="BCD798549B27370FFF5F1E6DFEEDF7F4" box="[212,378,2057,2076]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="294">Hydrochus directus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A7E4252F9B27370FFEF41E6DFE53F7F4" box="[383,452,2057,2076]" pageId="3" pageNumber="294" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, habitus and male genitalia of holotype.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B203708FF3E173AFE17FCDD" blockId="4.[151,760,188,1013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="169858C39B203708FEEA173AFE33FE9D" box="[353,420,350,373]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[151,182,2059,2078]" captionTargetBox="[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[204,1384,841,2039]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Hydrochus debilis Sharp, 1882, habitus and male genitalia of lectotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3879766" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3879766/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). General characters: paramere tips moderately large, extending beyond distal tip of aedeagus, sagittate, distal ends pointed, lateral margins between 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FF7217DAFEB0FE3D" box="[249,295,446,469]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">plsa</emphasis>
and distal end slightly emarginate, medial margins of tips very slightly arcuate toward midline and well separated from lateral margins of aedeagus; parameres in dorsal/ventral views constricted at base of tips and dorsally with low ridge; parameres in dorsal/ventral views much wider at widest point than tips; parameres in lateral view wide, sinuate, and tapering to sharp tips; aedeagus greatest width at 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FE3714FAFE7BFD5D" box="[444,492,670,693]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">adbl</emphasis>
, shaft (portion of aedeagus distal to 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FEAC14DAFEC0FD3D" box="[295,343,702,725]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">adbl</emphasis>
) in dorsal/ventral views very narrow, almost parallel-sided; aedeagus dorsal margin sinuate in lateral view; basal piece shorter than parameres, with rim of orifice sclerotized.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B203708FF3E155AFD71FC5D" blockId="4.[151,760,188,1013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">
Dorsal surface: 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FEEB155AFE1EFCBD" box="[352,393,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">adtl</emphasis>
located at about distal fifth of aedeagus; 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FF7B153AFEA6FC9D" box="[240,305,862,885]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">pdmm</emphasis>
very slightly narrowly overlapping 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FD3E153AFD4AFC9D" box="[693,733,862,885]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">alm</emphasis>
at about midlength of aedeagus; 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FE59151AFD96FC7D" box="[466,513,894,917]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">adbl</emphasis>
very large, much wider than paramere area lateral to 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FE4615FAFE6BFC5D" box="[461,508,926,949]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">adbl</emphasis>
, distinctively shaped.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E1C44469B203708FF3E15DAFE95FC1D" blockId="4.[151,760,188,1013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">
Ventral surface: 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FEEC15DBFE30FC3E" box="[359,423,959,982]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">pvmm</emphasis>
overlapping 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FDBD15DAFDC9FC3D" box="[566,606,958,981]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">alm</emphasis>
at base; 
<emphasis id="BCD798549B203708FD4A15DBFD6FFC3E" box="[705,760,959,982]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="295">pwsa</emphasis>
near base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
